<paragraph id="8BB40E2E6E604064FF485ECD147C9CDA" blockId="13.[151,1437,151,968]" pageId="13" pageNumber="274">
<emphasis id="B97FD23C6E604064FF485ECD15199DE2" bold="true" box="[199,532,727,752]" pageId="13" pageNumber="274">Comparisons and Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C0B75AD6E604064FD945EC215D19DE2" authorityName="Okamoto &amp; Motomura" authorityYear="2012" box="[539,732,728,752]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="274" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="exodon">
<emphasis id="B97FD23C6E604064FD945EC215D19DE2" box="[539,732,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="274">Epigonus exodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs the 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B75AD6E604064FCE65EC314FB9DE2" authorityName="Mayer" authorityYear="1974" box="[873,1014,728,752]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="274" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oligolepis">
<emphasis id="B97FD23C6E604064FCE65EC314FB9DE2" box="[873,1014,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="274">E. oligolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, defined as having less than 40 pored lateral-line scales (
<figureCitation id="133012AB6E604064FE395EE615129C06" box="[438,543,764,789]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1827,1849]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,926,1805]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[188,1398,901,1805]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 10. Epigonus exodon, MNHN 1991-0155, holotype, 97.0 mm SL. Overall body (A); and dorsal (B) and ventral (C) views of tipof the lower jaw, arrows show the anteriorly projecting teeth." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1182187/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="274">Fig. 10A</figureCitation>
), lacking an opercular spine and ribs on the last abdominal vertebra. It can be easily distinguished from other congeners of the 
<collectingRegion id="49CFC0CC6E604064FD405F3A14279C25" box="[719,810,800,823]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="Western" pageId="13" pageNumber="274">Western</collectingRegion>
Indian Ocean by having 35–37 lateral-line scales and anteriorly projecting teeth on the symphysis of lower jaw (vs. more than 45 lateral-line scales and lacking projecting teeth on the symphysis of lower jaw in other congeners; 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B75AD6E604064FC005F7313299C92" authorityName="Okamoto &amp; Gon" authorityYear="2018" box="[911,1060,872,896]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="274" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bispinosus">
<emphasis id="B97FD23C6E604064FC005F7313299C92" box="[911,1060,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="274">E. bispinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has two spines on the symphysis of lower jaw). 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A73DF6E604064FECF5F9615949CB6" box="[320,665,908,933]" pageId="13" pageNumber="274" refId="ref21276" refString="Okamoto, M., Bartsch, P. &amp; Motomura, H. (2012) Epigonus merleni, a junior synonym of Epigonus macrops (Actinopterygii: Perciformes: Epigonidae). Species Diversity, 17, 123 - 126. https: // doi. org / 10.12782 / sd. 17.2.123" type="journal article">Okamoto &amp; Motomura (2012)</bibRefCitation>
reported an ontogenetic change in the anteriorly projecting teeth of the lower jaw (
<typeStatus id="54B0B08C6E604064FEB15FAA16AE9CDA" box="[318,419,944,968]" pageId="13" pageNumber="274">paratype</typeStatus>
, 
<quantity id="4CF3A3CB6E604064FE215FB5151F9CD5" box="[430,530,943,968]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.02" pageId="13" pageNumber="274" unit="mm" value="60.2">60.2 mm</quantity>
SL, lacks the projecting teeth).
</paragraph>
